PSEUDORABIES, SWINE - USA (NEW JERSEY)
**************************************
A ProMED post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
See Also
Pseudorabies, swine - USA 990212210853
Pseudorabies, swine - USA (02) 990217110027
Date: Tue, 07 Sep 1999 11:30:04 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Boston Globe (edited) and Associate Press 7 Sept. 99 (edited)

State agriculture officials ordered a quarantine of swine within a 2-mile
radius of the Messner-Widing farm while they monitor the outbreak of
pseudorabies, a highly contagious viral infection thought to have been
eradicated in New Jersey 4 years ago.
More than 320 hogs on the farm were destroyed following the diagnosis last
month, said Ernest Zirkle, an animal health official with the state
Department of Agriculture.
Other pigs on farms in Gloucester and nearby Camden and Burlington counties
will be tested for exposure to the virus, Zirkle said.
Pseudorabies, which is related to herpes, causes serious respiratory
problems and stillbirths in hogs. It is not harmful to humans.
Because the virus poses a serious threat to the nation's pork producers,
the U.S. Department of Agriculture 10 years ago launched a pseudorabies
eradication program, which includes vaccinations.
Zirkle said the source of the latest New Jersey outbreak appears to be a
livestock dealer in Pennsylvania. The Messner-Widing farm purchased the
hogs in Lancaster County.
New Jersey farms had been disease-free for 4 years. More than 6,800 hogs
are infected and under quarantine in Pennsylvania, USDA records show.
The sick New Jersey hogs were incinerated Aug. 24 at a facility in Indiana,
Zirkle said.
