[Pseudorabies virus is a DNA heres virus Although the pig is the only
natural host, the virus can infect cattle, sheep, cats, dogs, and goats as
well as such feral animals as raccoons, opossums, skunks and rodents.
Experimental studies in non-human primates indicate rhesus monkeys and
marmosets are susceptible but chimpanzees are not. Reports of human
infection are limited and are based on seroconversion rather than virus
isolation. Infection in horses are rare.
Transmission of the virus can occur via nose-to-nose or fecal-oral contact.
Indirect transmission commonly occurs via inhalation of aerosolized virus.
Infectious virus can persist for up to 7 hours in air with a relative
humidity of greater than or equal to 55 percent. Data from England indicate
that virus may travel via aerosols for up to 2km in certain weather
conditions. Other studies have demonstrated the virus can survive for 2
days in anaerobic lagoon effluent and in green grass, soil, feces and
shelled corn, 3 days in nasal washings on plastic and pelleted hog feed and
4 days in straw bedding.
Generally, the signs are those of central nervous system (CNS) disease and
include such things as tremors and paddling. Respiratory disease may be a
problem in weaned pigs. Pigs of all ages have a generalized febrile
response, anorexia and weight loss.
Although there is no specific treatment for acute infection with
pseudorabies virus, vaccination can alleviate clinical signs in pigs of
certain ages. Mass vaccination all pigs on the farm with a modified live
virus vaccine is usually recommended.
Pseudorabies is a reportable disease. Is Lancaster County Pennsylvania one
of the counties in Pennsylvania that is quarantined? If so, how did the pig
get sold to New Jersey? - Mod.TG
